Problem: The ${ }^7 \mathrm{Li}^1 \mathrm{H}$ ground electronic state has $D_0=2.4287 \mathrm{eV}, \nu_e / c=1405.65 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$, and $\nu_e x_e / c=23.20 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$, where $c$ is the speed of light. (These last two quantities are usually designated $\omega_e$ and $\omega_e x_e$ in the literature.) Calculate $D_e$ for ${ }^7 \mathrm{Li}^1 \mathrm{H}$. The unit of the answer should be  $\mathrm{eV}$.
Solution: I need to find $D_e$ (dissociation energy at the bottom of the potential well) from $D_0$ (dissociation energy from the ground vibrational state).

The relationship between $D_e$ and $D_0$ involves the zero-point vibrational energy:

$$D_e = D_0 + E_{\text{vib}}(v=0)$$

where the zero-point vibrational energy is given by:

$$E_{\text{vib}}(v=0) = \frac{1}{2}\hbar\omega_e - \frac{1}{4}\hbar\omega_e x_e$$

Or in terms of wavenumbers (using $\hbar\omega = hc\tilde{\nu}$):

$$E_{\text{vib}}(v=0) = \frac{1}{2}hc\frac{\nu_e}{c} - \frac{1}{4}hc\frac{\nu_e x_e}{c}$$

Converting wavenumbers to eV using $1 \text{ cm}^{-1} = 1.23984 \times 10^{-4} \text{ eV}$:

$$\frac{\nu_e}{c} = 1405.65 \text{ cm}^{-1} \times 1.23984 \times 10^{-4} \text{ eV/cm}^{-1} = 0.174297 \text{ eV}$$

$$\frac{\nu_e x_e}{c} = 23.20 \text{ cm}^{-1} \times 1.23984 \times 10^{-4} \text{ eV/cm}^{-1} = 0.002876 \text{ eV}$$

The zero-point energy is:

$$E_{\text{vib}}(v=0) = \frac{1}{2}(0.174297) - \frac{1}{4}(0.002876)$$

$$E_{\text{vib}}(v=0) = 0.087149 - 0.000719 = 0.086430 \text{ eV}$$

Therefore:

$$D_e = D_0 + E_{\text{vib}}(v=0)$$

$$D_e = 2.4287 + 0.086430 = 2.515130 \text{ eV}$$

Rounding to appropriate significant figures (5 sig figs based on the given data):

$$D_e = 2.5151 \text{ eV}$$

